Research Proposal

The question that I want to explore in this project is whether or not the Oscar Academy Awards are guilty of lacking diversity in nominating African American actors.

This week, Kevin Hart announced that he would not be hosting the Oscars, in revolt to the lack of African American actors being nominated for the Academy Awards.

This controversy started back in 2016, on the 30th anniversary of Martin Luther King Jr. day, when many prominent African American celebrities such as Spike Lee and Jada Pinkett Smith decided to boycott the Oscars. They wanted to highlight the fact that in 2 years, the Oscars had not nominated a single African American actor for an award.

This conversation about a lack of diversity in nominating African American actors came up once again in my Screenwriting class this semster. On reviewing the list of 2018 Oscar nominees for best picture, we realised that out of the 9 movies, only 1 had an African American actor in a lead role.

Following this discussion, our class was divided into 2 groups with different views on the problem:

The first view as discussed earlier was that the Oscars are guilty of lacking diversity in nominating African American actors.

The other view was that, the Oscars cannot be blamed for being racist and for not nominating enough African American actors for awards, because of the sheer lack of African American actors hired in movies.

People from the second group, including me, feel that this lack of diversity is a result of Hollywood studios and cable networks not producing enough movies with African American lead actors, instead of the Oscars being prejudiced.

I wanted to dig deeper into this issue in order to find out the truth of the matter, and through this project I propose to answer this question.

Data Collection

First, I have used the US Census data and US Actors data, in order to calculate the percentage of the population that is African American in each group, to investigate if the African American population is proportionately represented in the Acting community.

To perform my analysis, I decided to use the Top IMDB rated movies since 2010 and compare it to Oscar nominated movies since 2010.

I used an online random number generator, in order to select 50 movies from each data set, which corresponded to the respective numbers randomly. I then looked online at the cast of each movie on IMDB, to determine if the movies had a African American Actors in a lead role.

The data frame created in Part 1 stores the values for the number of African American actors in lead roles for Best Movies on IMDB and Oscar Nominated Movies.

Using this data, I calculated the percentage of African American lead actors to Non-African American lead actors in both data sets.

The idea is to basically find out if there is a general lack of African American Actors in successful Hollywood movies, or that, in spite, of being part of successful Hollywood movies, the Oscars wont nominate African American actors proportionately.

Hypothesis Testing

Null Hypothesis = 1 - 2 = 0 (Not Guilty of lacking diveristy)

Alternate Hypothesis = 1 - 2 > 0 (Guilty of lacking diveristy)

Alpha = 0.05

prop.test(c(15, 10), c(50, 50), correct = FALSE)
## 
##  2-sample test for equality of proportions without continuity
##  correction
## 
## data:  c(15, 10) out of c(50, 50)
## X-squared = 1.3333, df = 1, p-value = 0.2482
## alternative hypothesis: two.sided
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.06860248  0.26860248
## sample estimates:
## prop 1 prop 2 
##    0.3    0.2

Results

We find that the p-value is 0.2482, which is greater than the our significance level of 0.05 Since our p-value is greater than our alpha level, we fail to reject the Null Hypothesis.

With 95% confidence, we can say that the difference in the Number of Top 50 Movies with Black leads and the Number of Oscar Nominated Movies with Black leads is in between -0.07 and 0.27.

Therefore, we have proved our Null Hypothesis that the Oscars are not guilty of lacking diveristy in nominating African American Actors, because the number of Movies nominated to the Oscars with a Black lead is proportional to the number of movies with a Black Lead that was rated highly in IMDB.
